          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2621" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Regional Associations</heading>
               <p id="IO-UN.2622">Members are grouped in six Regional Associations (Africa, Asia, Europe, North America, Central America and the Caribbean, South America and the South-West Pacific), whose task is to co-ordinate meteorological activity within their regions and to examine questions referred to them by the Executive Council. Sessions are held at least once every four years. WMO has Geneva-based regional offices for Europe and Africa, an Asunción, Paraguay-based regional office for the Americas, and a Singapore-based regional office for Asia and the South-West Pacific.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2623" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Technical Commissions</heading>
               <p>The Commissions, for Observation, Infrastructure and Information Systems and for Weather, Climate, Hydrological, Marine and Related Environmental Services and Applications are composed of experts nominated by the members of WMO. Sessions are held at least once every four years. There is also a Research Board and a Technical Coordination Committee.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO.WMO.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Scientific Advisory Panel</heading>
               <p>The Panel, comprising up to 15 international scientific experts, advises the Congress and Executive Council on research strategies and long-term scientific priorities.</p>
          </int-org-section>
     </int-org-section>
     <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2625" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Activities</heading>
          <p>In June 2023 the 19th World Meteorological Congress approved a strategic plan to guide WMO’s activities during the period 2024-27. The plan’s overall objective was to ensure, by end-2027, that everyone on Earth is protected against hazardous weather by life-saving early warning systems. It had the following overarching priorities: (i) Enhancing preparedness and reducing loss of life, critical infrastructure and livelihood from hydrometeorological extremes; (ii) Supporting climate-smart decision-making to build or enhance adaptive capacity or resilience to climate risk; and (iii) Enhancing socioeconomic value of weather, climate, hydrological and related environmental services. The longer-term goals to be achieved by 2030 focused on better serving societal needs through the delivery of appropriate accessible information and services; enhancing Earth system observations and predictions; strengthening the technical foundation for future activities; advancing targeted research; closing the capacity gap on weather, climate, hydrological and related environmental services; and implementing a realignment of WMO structure and programmes to enhance policy making and the making and implementation of decisions.</p>
          <p usage="edio">The 19th World Meteorological Congress also approved a resolution focused on the goal of achieving gender equality through the provision of gender-sensitive weather, hydrological and climate services that respond to the specific needs and socioeconomic circumstances of both women and men; furthermore, the Congress confirmed that, as a minimum target, women should fill at least 40% of roles in the working structures of related regional associations, technical commissions and of the WMO Research Board.</p>
          <p>
      In March 2024 WMO’s 
      <publ-name>State of the Global Climate</publ-name>
       confirmed that 2023 had been, by a clear margin, the hottest year since records began in 1850, with potentially devastating implications for natural ecosystems and the environment.
    </p>
          <p usage="edio">In March 2023 the UN General Assembly adopted a resolution that requested the International Court of Justice to provide an Advisory Opinion on: (i) nations’ obligations under international law to ensure the protection for present and future generations of the climate system and other parts of the environment from greenhouse gas emissions, and (ii) on the legal consequences for nations that cause significant harm to the climate system and other parts of the environment.</p>
          <int-org-section id="WMO.IO.FORECAST.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Analysis and Forecast</heading>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>WMO Integrated Processing and Prediction System (WIPPS)</heading>
                    <p>The WIPPS was formerly known as the Global Data-processing and Forecasting System, and renamed in June 2023. Aims to facilitate the generation and dissemination of quality analyses and forecasts, designed to assist members in making local and specialized forecasts. The System consisted in 2024 of 142 designated centres—including 10 World Meteorological Centres (WMCs) in: Beijing (People’s Republic of China), Melbourne (Australia), Montreal (Canada), Moscow (Russian Federation), Offenbach (Germany), Reading (United Kingdom), Tokyo (Japan), Toulouse (France), Washington, DC (USA), and the Exeter, UK-based European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF); and 12 regional climate prediction and monitoring centres. Centres provide analyses, forecasts and warnings for exchange on the Global Telecommunications System. Some centres concentrate on the monitoring and forecasting of environmental quality and special weather phenomena, such as tropical cyclones, monsoons, droughts, etc., which have a major impact on human safety and national economies.</p>
                    <p>In June 2019 the 18th World Meteorological Congress endorsed a WMO Data Catalogue, combining (initially) 18 internationally recognized global climate datasets, for use by decision makers.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>World Climate Research Programme (WCRP)</heading>
                    <p>
          Organized jointly with UNESCO’s Intergovernmental Oceanographic Commission (IOC) and the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="OTHER-IO-SCIENCE.ISC.1">International Science Council</xr>
          , to determine to what extent climate can be predicted, and the extent of man's influence on climate. The WCRP Strategic Plan 2019-28 had the following priority objectives: (i) advancing the fundamental understanding of processes, variations and changes in the climate system; (ii) predicting the near-term evolution of the climate system; (iii) refining the ability to anticipate future pathways of climate system change; and (iv) promoting the development of theory and practice in the integration between natural and social sciences. The following four WCRP core projects were being implemented during 2019-28: Climate and Cryosphere (CliC); Climate and Ocean—Variability, Predictability and Change (CLIVAR); Global Energy and Water Exchanges (GEWEX); and Stratosphere-troposphere Processes And their Role in Climate (SPARC). It was announced in December 2020 that the functioning of the Programme was to be streamlined to support the implementation of the ongoing Strategic Plan. In that month the WCRP and Future Earth—a global network of scientists, innovators and researchers—signed an agreement on future co-operation. In June 2015 the 17th Congress inaugurated WCRP Grand Science Challenges, to comprise projects with a focus on high-priority research, that require support from international partnerships. In 2023 Challenges were implemented with a focus on melting ice and global consequences, clouds, circulation and climate sensitivity, carbon feedbacks in the climate system, weather and climate extremes, water for the food baskets of the world, regional sea level change and coastal impacts, and near-term climate prediction. WCRP’s Open Science Conference was held in Kigali, Rwanda, and in a virtual format, in October 2023.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>World Weather Research Programme (WWRP)</heading>
                    <p>The WWRP promotes the development and application of improved weather forecasting techniques. It is primarily concerned with forecasting weather events that have the potential to cause considerable socioeconomic dislocation. Activities underway during 2024 included an Aviation Research Demonstration Project; the Polar Prediction Project (q.v.); and a Tropical Cyclone-Probabilistic Forecast Products initiative.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Global Hydrological Status and Outlook System (HydroSOS)</heading>
                    <p>HydroSOS aims to enhance national capacities across the hydrological value chain.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="WMO.IO.OBSERVE.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Observation and Monitoring</heading>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>WMO Integrated Global Observing System (WIGOS)</heading>
                    <p>The initial operational phase of WIGOS commenced on 1 January 2020. It was intended to be the core element of WMO’s observation infrastructure, supporting all relevant programmes and applications. WIGOS aims to develop international and national partnerships, in order to enhance the effective collection, processing and dissemination of data in support of sustainable development objectives. WMO observations are gathered from around 10,000 land stations and 1,300 upper-air stations. A WIGOS Data Quality Monitoring System was launched in March 2020 to survey the accessibility and reliability of these stations at any one time. Meteorological information is also received from 4,000 aircraft, 7,300 ships, 1,250 drifting ocean buoys, 400 moored buoys, nearly 1,000 weather balloons, and more than 50 meteorological satellites (both polar orbiting and geostationary). An Extraordinary World Meteorological Congress that was held in October 2021 approved a WMO Unified Data Policy (to guide the international exchange of climate, weather and related Earth system data), Systematic Observations Financing Facility (SOFF, q.v.), and a new Global Basic Observing Network (GBON) to enhance surface-based observation.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Global Climate Observing System (GCOS)</heading>
                    <p>
          Comprises a terrestrial network of around 1,000 observation stations. Aims to ensure that data on climate are obtained and made available for climate system monitoring and climate change detection and attribution; assessing impacts of, and vulnerability to, climate variability and change, e.g. extreme events, terrestrial ecosystems, etc., and analysing options for adaptation; research to improve understanding, modelling and prediction of the climate system; and application to sustainable economic development. The strategy of the GCOS has been to work with its international and regional partners and to engage countries both directly and through international fora. 
          <publ-name>The Global Climate Observing System 2021: The GCOS Status Report,</publ-name>
           issued in September of that year (and representing the fifth report in a longstanding series), noted significant advancements since 2015 both in satellite and surface-based observations, while also identifying remaining gaps, including the need to ensure permanent unrestricted access to observations. WMO supported the organization of the 2nd Climate Observation Conference, held in October 2022, in Darmstadt, Germany.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Centennial Observing Stations</heading>
                    <p>By April 2024 WMO had formally recognized 404 centennial observing stations globally (372 meteorological, 22 hydrological and 10 marine), that maintain very long-term weather observation records. In October 2021 WMO accredited the upper air observing station of the Hong Kong Observatory as the first centennial upper air observing station.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Instruments and Methods of Observation Programme (IMOP)</heading>
                    <p>The IMOP sets quality control procedures and technical standards, and guides the design and usage of instruments and observation methods. </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Space Programme</heading>
                    <p>The 14th WMO Congress, held in 2003, initiated this cross-cutting programme to increase the effectiveness of, and contributions from, satellite systems for WMO-supported programmes and associated observing systems. Congress recognized the critical importance of data, products and services provided by the expanded space-based component of the GCOS. The Executive Council subsequently resolved to expand the space-based component of the GCOS to include appropriate research and development (R&amp;D) and environmental satellite missions. The four main components of the Programme are: developing an integrated space-based observing system; ensuring availability and use of satellite data and products; information and training, including implementing the strategy of a WMO-Coordination Group for Meterological Satellites (CGMS) Virtual Laboratory for Training and Education in Satellite Meteorology; and space weather co-ordination.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="WMO.IO.EXCH.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Exchange Data</heading>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Global Atmosphere Watch (GAW)</heading>
                    <p>GAW integrates monitoring and research activities involving the long-term measurement of atmospheric composition, and is intended to serve as an early warning system to detect further changes under the following principal focal areas: total atmospheric composition; greenhouse gases; ozone; aerosol; selected reactive gases; and ultraviolet (UV) radiation. GAW is the main contributor of data on chemical composition and surface UV radiation to the Global Climate Observing System (GCOS). GAW comprises a network of 30 global stations in remote areas of the world and around 400 regional stations. Regular shipborne research programmes and a network of contributing stations support GAW’s surface observation activities. These are complemented by space-based satellite and airborne observations of the lower stratosphere and upper troposphere, which assess levels of solar radiation, ozone, the atmospheric burden of aerosols, and various trace gases. GAW oversees the WMO Sand and Dust Storm Warning Advisory and Assessment System (SDS-WAS), and works with the advisory Joint Group of Experts on the Scientific Aspects of Marine Environmental Protection (GESAMP).</p>
                    <p>
          Since 2006 GAW has prepared an annual 
          <publ-name>Greenhouse Gas Bulletin</publ-name>
           to report on the main emitted gases on the atmosphere, including long-lived greenhouse gases (LLGHGs), and to provide scientific evidence for policy and decision making. Quality Assurance/Science Activity Centres have been established to ensure an overall level of quality in GAW. Atmospheric composition information is maintained by a series of seven GAW World Data Centres: the World Data Center for Remote Sensing of the Atmosphere (in Wessling, Germany), and further centres covering ozone and UV; solar radiation; greenhouse gases; reactive gases; aerosols; and precipitation chemistry. GAW’s Urban Environment Meteorological Research Programme (GURME) assists NMHSs in dealing with regional and urban pollution monitoring and forecasting, through the provision of guidelines and information on the requisite measuring and modelling infrastructures, and by bringing together NMHSs, regional and city administrations and health authorities. GURME is being developed in co-operation with the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.2442">World Health Organization (WHO)</xr>
          .
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Global Cryosphere Watch (GCW)</heading>
                    <p>WMO considers the polar regions (including the `Third Pole’—the Himalayan and Tibetan Plateau) as extremely important in terms of their impact on global weather, water and climate. The 16th World Meteorological Congress (2011) supported the need to establish an observational framework for polar regions, including an Antarctic Observing Network; determined to support a Global Integrated Polar Prediction System; and decided to develop, with international partners, the GCW. The Congress emphasized the significance, in terms of climate change prediction, of the cryosphere—i.e. water in its frozen state, including snow cover, sea, lake and river ice, glaciers, ice caps, ice sheets and permafrost, spanning all latitudes, in approximately 100 countries. WMO established a Polar Space Task Group and subsidiary Synthetic Aperture Radar Coordination Working Group in 2011; these were tasked with improving the co-ordination of the collection of satellite radar data in the polar regions and cryosphere. In 2015 the 17th World Meteorological Congress decided that the GCW should be implemented henceforth as a cross-cutting activity. The GCW’s Snow Watch Team conducts assessments of snow and solid precipitation.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Global Greenhouse Gas Watch (G3W)</heading>
                    <p>
          In March 2023 the WMO Executive Council endorsed a new G3W Infrastructure, combining satellite and terrestrial observations. WMO has contributed to the development of an Integrated Global Greenhouse Gas Information System (IG3IS); in this context 
          <publ-name>IG3IS Urban Greenhouse Gas Emission Observation and Monitoring Best Research Practices</publ-name>
           was issued in August 2021.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>WMO Hydrological Observing System (WHOS)</heading>
                    <p>The WHOS provides a framework for the reliable exchange of hydrological data. A WMO HydroHub—to provide a sustainable and efficient source of hydrological data and information—was established in 2016. A World Hydrological Cycle Observing System focuses on strengthening the technical and human capabilities of NMHSs in the areas of information production, collection and dissemination. A Water and Climate Leaders Panel met for the first time in March 2021, under WMO auspices, with the aim of developing integrated action on water and climate in support of the implementation of the UN Sustainable Development Goals. The Extraordinary WMO Congress that was convened in October adopted a Vision and Strategy for Hydrology and associated plan of action, which set the following long-term goals: (i) No one is surprised by a flood; (ii) Everyone is prepared for drought; (iii) Hydro-climate and meteorological data support the food security agenda; (iv) High-quality data supports science; (v) Science provides a sound basis for operational hydrology; (vi) We have a thorough knowledge of the water resources of our world; (vii) Sustainable development is supported by hydrological information; and (viii) Water quality is known. During November 2022 a WMO-supported inter-agency Action for Water Adaptation and Resilience (AWARe) initiative was launched. In June 2023 a dedicated Hydrological Assembly was convened during the 19th World Meteorological Congress. The 19th Congress determined to enhance implementation of the ongoing plan of action for the implementation of the Vision and Strategy for Hydrology.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>WMO Information System (WIS)</heading>
                    <p>The WIS became operational in January 2012 as a single co-ordinated global infrastructure responsible for telecommunications and data management, aimed at expanding the global exchange of meteorological, climate, hydrological and ocean data. The core infrastructure of the WIS comprises Global Information System Centres (GISCs), of which there were 15 in 2023, as well as data collection or production centres, and national centres. A WIS 2.0 phase, introduced in December 2022, supports a new Global Basic Observing Network and WMO Unified Data policy. (Both were approved in October 2021, and aim to enhance real-time international, regional and national data sharing.) Eventually the WIS was to supersede the Global Telecommunication System (q.v.). An open-source WIS2 in a box software supports LDCs and SIDs with the implementation of WIS 2.0.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="WMO.IO.RES.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Building Resilience</heading>
               <p>Through its scientific and technical programmes and network of meteorological and climate centres, WMO provides observational, monitoring, prediction and early warning services in respect of a wide range of weather-, climate- and water-related hazards. In March 2015, at the third UN World Conference on DDR, which adopted the Sendai Framework for DDR (2015-30), WMO confirmed that it would provide support to member states in establishing Multi-Hazard Early Warning Systems (MHEWS). DRR activities relevant to the Sendai Framework are integrated across WMO’s programming. In June 2019 the 18th World Meteorological Congress endorsed a series of measures aimed at strengthening MHEWS and at including these in humanitarian operations. The Congress determined to promote the implementation of a new Global Multi-hazard Alert System that was under development by a WMO expert group at that time. The Congress noted the special need to enhance early warning services in urban areas, owing to their vulnerability to multiple hazards, such as poor air quality, heatwaves and flooding. Global co-operation in combating sand and dust storms was to be enhanced.</p>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Early Warnings for All</heading>
                    <p>
          WMO and the UN Office for Disaster Risk Reduction co-lead the inter-agency Early Warnings for All initiative that was launched in November 2022 by the UN Secretary-General, and aimed to put in place a worldwide early warning system by the end of 2027. The initiative aims to strengthen the four pillars that underpin (MHEWS): Disaster risk knowledge; Detection, observation, monitoring, analysis, and forecasting; Warning dissemination and communication; and Preparedness and response capabilities. Achieving Early Warnings for All requires broad partnerships at the global, regional, and national levels in support of the most vulnerable and at risk. WMO maintains an online Early Warnings for All Dashboard, and issues an annual 
          <publ-name>Global Status of Multi-Hazard Early Warning Systems</publ-name>
           report. In May 2022 WMO helped to organize the third MHEWS Conference, in Bali, Indonesia. With the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) WMO has established procedures and response mechanisms for the provision and exchange of observational data and specialized transport model products in the event of a nuclear accident. In the framework of WMO’s Emergency Response Activities Programme, 10 regional specialized meteorological centres are on continuous stand by to provide a nuclear environmental emergency response.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Systematic Observation Financing Facility (SOFF)</heading>
                    <p>
          WMO was a founding agency, with UNDP and the UN Environment Programme (
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.1369">UNEP</xr>
          
          ), of the Systematic Observation Financing Facility (SOFF) which was launched in June 2022 to support early warning forecasting and weather services.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Associated Programme on Flood Management</heading>
                    <p>The Associated Programme on Flood Management, jointly sponsored by WMO and the Global Water Partnership, provides, through its Integrated Flood Management Helpdesk, guidance, capacity building support, and assistance with the development of project proposals. In June 2023, to improve overall water resources management, the 19th World Meteorological Congress endorsed an expansion of the Helpdesk (and of the parallel Helpdesk on Integrated Drought Management). The 19th Congress also approved strengthened flood forecasting initiatives. WMO co-ordinates a Flash Flood Guidance System Network of regional and national centres to enhance early-warning and protection measures.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Integrated Drought Management Programme (IDMP)</heading>
                    <p>
          A joint initiative with the Global Water Partnership, the IDMP focuses on the following three pillars: Drought monitoring and early warning systems; Vulnerability and impact assessments; and Drought preparedness, mitigation and response. It has been guided by decisions of the High-level Meeting on National Drought Policy, which was convened in March 2013, in Geneva, under the auspices of WMO, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the UN (
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.1742">FAO</xr>
          ), and the Secretariat of the UN Convention to Combat Desertification. The IDMP sets guidelines and extends advice through a Helpdesk on Integrated Drought Management.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Severe Weather Forecasting Programme (SWFP)</heading>
                    <p>The Severe Weather Forecasting Programme (SWFP) works in around 85 developing states to enhance national capacity to deliver severe weather forecasts and warnings, with a view to protecting lives, livelihoods, property and infrastructure.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Tropical Cyclone Programme</heading>
                    <p>
          WMO’s Tropical Cyclone Programme aims to develop national and regionally co-ordinated systems to ensure that the loss of life and damage caused by tropical cyclones and associated floods, landslides and storm surges are reduced to a minimum. The Programme supports the transfer of technology, and the sharing of information and scientific knowledge. Its regional component supports the planning, forecasting and warning activities of the following five regional tropical cyclone bodies: 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.1010">the ESCAP/WMO Typhoon Committee</xr>
          ; the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.1013">WMO/ESCAP Panel on Tropical Cyclones</xr>
          ; the Tropical Cyclone Committee for the South-West Indian Ocean; the Tropical Cyclone Committee for the South Pacific and South-East Indian Ocean; and the Hurricane Committee (covering North America, Central America and the Caribbean). The regional bodies contribute to a Storm Surge Watch Scheme which aims to improve weather warnings and disaster mitigation. Cyclone, hurricane or other meteorological forecasting information is provided by WMO’s six Regional Specialized Meteorological Centres in Nadi (Fiji), La Réunion, New Delhi (India), Tokyo (Japan), Honolulu (Hawaii) and Miami (USA), and four Tropical Cyclone Warning Centres in Jakarta (Indonesia), Melbourne (Australia), Port Moresby (Papua New Guinea) and Wellington (New Zealand).
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Climate Risk and Early Warning Systems (CREWS)</heading>
                    <p>In December 2015 WMO, the World Bank and other partners launched a global initiative which aimed, through the development of MHEWS, to strengthen the resilience of vulnerable nations to extreme weather and climate change. In 2019 the scope of the CREWS initiative was expanded to encompass up to 44 LDCs and SIDS. By 31 December 2022 a CREWS Trust Fund, established in 2016, had received donations totalling US&#8201;$95.2m. and had approved $74.1m. in project funding.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group id="EDIO">
                    <heading usage="edio">Regional Programme</heading>
                    <p usage="edio">WMO’s Regional Programme cuts across the other major WMO programmes of relevance to the regions and addresses meteorological, hydrological and other geophysical issues which are unique to and of common concern to a region or group of regions. It provides a framework for the formulation of most of the global WMO Programmes and serves as a mechanism for their implementation at national, subregional and regional level. The Programme provides support to the WMO regional associations and contributes to the development of NMHSs through capacity building and other priority activities identified by members or relevant economic groups and organizations within the respective regions. </p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="WMO.IO.SERVICES.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Delivery of Services</heading>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Agricultural Meteorology Programme</heading>
                    <p>
          The study of weather and climate as they affect agriculture and forestry, the selection of crops and their protection from disease and deterioration in storage, soil conservation, phenology and physiology of crops and productivity and health of farm animals. There are also special activities in agrometeorology to monitor and combat drought and desertification, and to monitor and control the risk posed by desert locusts. Maintains close co-operation with FAO, centres of the Consultative Group on International Agricultural Research (
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.1932">CGIAR</xr>
          ) and UNEP. The 16th World Meteorological Congress (in 2011) approved the use of a standardized meteorological drought index to enhance drought monitoring and early warning systems. A World Agro-Meteorological Information Service (WAMIS) is maintained.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Aviation Services</heading>
                    <p>
          WMO provides operational meteorological information required for safe, regular and efficient air navigation, as well as meteorological assistance to non-real-time activities of the aviation industry. The Programme, in co-operation with the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.2009">International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO)</xr>
           and other partners, promotes international standardization of methods, procedures and techniques. WMO and ICAO have collaborated on the development of a space-weather information service to facilitate international air navigation. In March 2024 WMO issued a new 
          <publ-name>Guide to Services for Aviation</publ-name>
          .
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Marine Services</heading>
                    <p>
          WMO helps member states to develop standards and procedures to elaborate a fully integrated state-of-the-art marine observing, data management, and services system. A Joint WMO/IOC Technical Commission for Oceanography and Marine Meteorology (JCOMM) manages and provides technical guidance to WMO’s Marine Meteorology and Oceanography Programme's (MMOP). Many programme elements are undertaken jointly with the IOC, within the context of JCOMM, and also of the Global Ocean Observing System (for which the IOC acts as secretariat). Close co-operation also occurs with the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.2129">International Maritime Organization</xr>
          , as well as with other bodies both within and outside the UN system. A JCOMM Observations Programme Support Centre (OceanOPS) is maintained. Annual Ocean Observing System Report Cards are issued by JCOMM. WMO and other agencies support the IOC with implementing tsunami warning systems for the Caribbean region, Indian Ocean, north-eastern Atlantic, Mediterranean and connected seas, and the Pacific.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Energy Services</heading>
                    <p>With a view to supporting the uptake of renewable energy, and bolstering the resilience of energy systems against extreme events and climate change impacts, WMO provides weather, water and climate information, for example through the GFCS. A WMO Study Group on Integrated Energy Services operates within the framework of the WMO Commission for Weather, Climate, Hydrological, Marine and Related Environmental Services and Applications.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>WHO-WMO Joint Climate and Health Programme</heading>
                    <p>WMO and WHO work together closely to advance integrated climate and health sciences and services. In July 2014 WMO established, with WHO, a Joint Office for Climate and Health. The Joint Office and the US National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration lead the Global Heat Health Information Network (comprising scientists, policy makers and practitioners). In May 2018 WMO, WHO, UNEP and the UN Climate Change collectively established a Health, Environment and Climate Change coalition. In June 2019 the 18th World Meteorological Congress endorsed a WMO-WHO Master Plan on Health, Environment, and Climate Science to Services, with a focus on the sustainable provision of integrated urban and health services. A joint WMO-WHO online ClimaHealth portal was launched in October 2022. In June 2023 the 19th World Meteorological Congress endorsed an Implementation Plan for Advancing Climate, Environment and Health Science and Services, covering the period 2023-33.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="WMO.IO.CAP.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Capacity Development</heading>
               <p>WMO supports the capacity development of NMHSs, with a particular focus on least developed countries (LDCs) and SIDS. The 18th World Meteorological Congress endorsed the establishment of an Alliance for Hydromet Development, with the aim of enhancing interconnected national, regional and global hydromet operational systems. (The Alliance was launched in December, and by 2024 had 14 participating organizations—including WMO, UNDP, UNEP, the Green Climate Fund, Climate Investment Funds.) The 18th Congress launched a Country Support Initiative to provide advisory technical assistance to developing countries and to development partners, with a view to overcoming capacity constraints to the provision of high-quality weather, climate and hydrological services.</p>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="edio">Education and Training Programme</heading>
                    <p id="IO-UN.2693" usage="edio">WMO assists members to develop adequately trained staff to meet their responsibilities for providing meteorological and hydrological information services. Activities include surveys of the training requirements of member states, the development of appropriate training programmes, the monitoring and improvement of the network of 23 Regional ­Meteorological Training Centres, the organization of training courses, seminars and conferences and the preparation of training materials. The Programme also arranges individual training programmes and the provision of fellowships. The Panel of Experts on Education and Training was established by the Executive Council to serve as an advisory body on all aspects of technical and scientific education and of training in meteorology and operational hydrology. In October 2020 a virtual WMO Hub Exchange Dialogue was initiated, with a focus on the delivery of distance learning.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group id="IO-UN.2699">
                    <heading usage="edio">Voluntary Co-operation Programme (VCP)</heading>
                    <p id="IO-UN.2700" usage="edio">WMO assists members in implementing the WWW Programme to develop an integrated observing and forecasting system. Member governments contribute equipment, services and fellowships for training, in addition to cash donations.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="WMO.IO.CLIM.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>State of the Global Climate</heading>
               <p>
        The 2023 
        <publ-name>State of the Global Climate</publ-name>
        , published in March 2024, confirmed that 2023 had been the hottest year since records began in 1850. Global average near-surface temperature were reported as having reached 1.45°C higher than pre-industrial levels, while carbon dioxide levels in the global atmosphere were 50% higher, causing heat to be trapped. Global mean sea level rises in 2023 reached a record high since relevant satellite records began in 1993, and more than 90% of the world’s ocean experienced heatwave conditions at some point during the year. Preliminary data indicated that WMO’s global set of reference glaciers had suffered the largest loss of ice since 1950 (when relevant records began), with Antarctic sea ice extent reported to be by far the lowest on record. The past decade had also been the warmest ten-year period on record. New climate-related records had been set in every month during June-December, and July and August were reported to be the two hottest months ever recorded. 
      </p>
               <p>
        WMO’s 
        <publ-name>The Global Climate 2011-2020: A Decade of Acceleration</publ-name>
        , issued in December 2023, documented impacts of rapid climate change on, 
        <i>inter alia,</i>
         displacement, migration and food security. It also reported on improvements in forecasts, early warnings and co-ordinated disaster management and response.
      </p>
               <p>WMO provides regular updates on the warm (El Niño) and cold (La Niña) phases of the climatic phenomenon known as El Niño Southern Oscillation (ENSO), which have onwards economic and social impacts on affected countries. In January 2024 WMO forecast that the year ahead might be hotter than 2023, given that mid-year a warming El Niño event was expected to replace a rare triple-dip `La Niña’ event—i.e. lasting three consecutive years—that during 2020-22 had produced a temporary slightly cooling climatic effect.</p>
               <p>In December 2023 WMO released updated guidelines on the evaluation of new climate records. In January 2024 the organization’s Weather and Climate Extremes Archive confirmed a new record high temperature for continental Europe, of 48.8°C, which occurred on 11 August 2021, in Sicily, Italy. According to the Archive the hottest ever temperature recorded globally (at 56.7°C) had occurred at Furnace Creek, Death Valley, California on 10 July 1913. In June 2019 it confirmed that very extreme temperatures had recently been verified at Mitribah, Kuwait (of 53.9°C, on 21 July 2016—a record high temperature for continental Asia) and at Turbat, Pakistan (53.7°C, on 28 May 2017).</p>
               <!--pre-industrial levels elaborated as 1850- 1900-->
               <!--~ average global temperature on 7.vii.23: a record 17.24 degrees C; previous record of 16.94 C on 16.viii.16-->
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2703" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Co-operation with Other Bodies</heading>
               <p>
        WMO, has concluded a number of formal agreements and working arrangements with international organizations both within and outside the UN system, at intergovernmental and non-governmental level. WMO provides the secretariat for a Panel on Tropical Cyclones. Several co-sponsored programmes are undertaken. In 1988 WMO, jointly with UNEP, established the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UNEP.101">Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change</xr>
         as an advisory scientific body concerned with assessing and reporting the scientific, technical and socioeconomic information relating to climate change. In response to the first report of the Panel, published in 1990, WMO and UNEP worked together to formulate the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UNEP.103">UN Framework Convention on Climate Change</xr>
         (UNFCCC), which was signed in May 1992 and entered into force in March 1994.
      </p>
               <p>WMO also carries out assistance projects under Trust Fund arrangements, financed by national authorities, either for activities in their own country or in a beneficiary country and managed by the UN Development Programme (UNDP), the World Bank, regional development banks, the European Union, and others. WMO provides assistance to UNDP in the development of NMHSs, in the application of meteorological and hydrological data to national economic development, and in the training of personnel.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2708" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>International Day</heading>
               <p>World Meteorological Day is observed every year, on 23 March. The theme for 2024 was `At the Frontline of Climate Action’.</p>
          </int-org-section>
     </int-org-section>
     <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2710" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Finance</heading>
          <p id="IO-UN.2711">WMO is financed by contributions from members on a proportional scale of assessment. In June 2023 the 19th World Meteorological Congress approved a regular budget of 278m. Swiss francs for the period 2024-27. Outside this budget, WMO implements a number of projects as executing agency for UNDP or else under trust fund arrangements.</p>
     </int-org-section>
